            ">TikTok vs RedNote</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.presidentialsummary.com/email/images/ps-jan-18-1.png" alt="TikTok vs RedNote" href="https://www.presidentialsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">The Supreme Court ruled Friday that a ban on TikTok can take effect this weekend, rejecting 
          the notion that the app owners' First Amendment challenge. In an unsigned opinion with no dissents, the court emphasized Congress's focus on <a href="https://link.presidentialsummary.com/ps-18-01-2025-bo-1-national-security-concerns" target="_blank">national security concerns</a> tied to TikTok's data collection practices and its links to China. The court follows Biden’s warning that the app poses a security threat. 170 million Americans use TikTok as a platform for engagement. The ban leaves a lot of unresolved questions about its enforcement, as this is the first ruling of this kind; there is no precedent.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">This ruling polishes off a weeklong saga regarding the app's situation. Speculation and rumors poured in regarding its potential purchase. The anxiety prompted many Americans to download the app RedNote this week, which brought many surprises and comical relief from Chinese and American users. However, the app will likely separate <a href="https://link.presidentialsummary.com/ps-18-01-2025-b0-2-mainland-chinese-content" target="_blank">mainland Chinese content</a> from other content shortly. Trump has given some hope to reverse the ban, claiming, “Congress has given me the decision, so I’ll be making the decision.” Parallelly, there was chaos at Meta, where the platform has gotten rid of fact-checkers, nixed their DEI initiatives, and brought changes to their hiring practices, which has garnered mixed reactions.</p>
        </mj-text> 
