              margin-top: 2px !important;
            ">How did Musk acquire Twitter?</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">Elon Musk acquired Twitter in 2022 after a high-profile and contentious process. The deal was seen as one of the largest tech acquisitions in history, and it sparked debates about the future of social media, free speech, and the role of billionaires in controlling online platforms. It also set a precedent in social media and partly explains current social media app issues, particularly content moderation and staff cuts. Here is a timeline of how it happened.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">In early <strong>April 2022</strong>, Musk began buying shares of Twitter, eventually becoming the largest individual shareholder with a 9.2% stake. On April 14, he made an unsolicited offer to buy the company outright for $44 billion (about $54.20 per share), a premium over Twitter's stock price. Twitter's board resisted Musk's offer. After negotiations, including concerns Musk raised regarding bots and spam accounts on the platform, Twitter's board ultimately accepted Musk's offer on April 25, 2022.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">By <strong>July 2022</strong>, Musk attempted to back out of the deal, citing concerns over the number of fake accounts on Twitter, which he argued were not accurately represented in Twitter's public filings. Twitter sued Musk, demanding that he go through with the acquisition, after a lengthy legal battle, countersuit, and public drama. When the countersuit didn’t seem to favor Musk over Twitter, Musk reversed his decision to terminate the deal and agreed to proceed with the acquisition at the original price.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">On <strong>October 28, 2022</strong>, he officially took control of Twitter. Musk quickly made changes, including firing top executives, making significant staff cuts, renaming the app, implementing a new strategy for content moderation, and shifting the platform's policies. He also focused on monetization by introducing a paid verification system (<a href="https://link.presidentialsummary.com/ps-18-01-2025-bq-8-timeline-of-twitter-acquisition" target="_blank">timeline of Twitter acquisition</a>).</p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
